  "slug": "lemon-tart-au-citron",
  "title": "Tarte au citron",
  "subtitle": "French set lemon-cream tart in a sweet shortcrust",
  "excerpt": "The French set lemon tart: a sweet shortcrust shell blind-baked, filled with a sharp lemon-cream mixture, and baked low until the centre is just set. One 23 cm tart, serving eight.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Marie-Antoine Carême, L'Art de la cuisine française (1833), Project Gutenberg: documents the French citron tart in its classical form. Urbain Dubois, La Cuisine Classique (1856), Project Gutenberg (French): documents the lemon-cream filling technique. Eliza Acton, Modern Cookery for Private Families (1845): documents the British lemon-curd tart that parallels the French form.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Tarte au citron is a French set-custard tart: a sweet shortcrust shell blind-baked pale gold, filled with a sharp mixture of egg yolks, sugar, lemon juice and cream, and baked at a low oven temperature until the filling just sets. The shell is precise (a thin, even crust), the filling is sharp, and the bake is patient.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Use unwaxed lemons, the zest goes in the filling and any wax leaches a bitter note. Strain the filling through a fine sieve before pouring into the shell; the strain catches any chalazae (the little stringy bits in eggs) and any zest pieces that would mar the smooth surface.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
